Cook,<br><br>
I appreciate, and thank you for, your personal insight into this vexing problem. It helps me just to know that there is one who has come to terms with it. The way for me will surely come with time, in its time.<br><br>
I am not a religious person. My way through my Vietnam experience has rekindled an old spirituality which was lost there. What matters most is that I re-define my humanity in terms of myself and not in the terms of others.<br><br>
Ed,<br><br>
Your last post was quite a story, and one that you clearly treasure, as you should. It brings home the remarkable qualities of being human that are frequently overshadowed by less important or more provocative events. It made me feel good to read it, too!   
<p><code>--   (Arthur Varanelli) </code><p>


